        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer249418546" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2496579813118407269">Great light mysteries with some insightful reflections on society. Asimov was BRILLIANT at using robots to reflect so clearly on the nature of humanity. A trick adeptly mastered in Star Trek The Next Generation&apos;s character &quot;Data&quot;. Using a non-human... non-LIVING no less!... character to point out both the depth and the shallowness of humans. This gives Asimov much more freedom because the reader can&apos;t dismiss the perspective of the robot (culture, background, circumstance, parenting, etc.) Anywa</span>
  <span id="freeText2496579813118407269" style="display:none">Great light mysteries with some insightful reflections on society. Asimov was BRILLIANT at using robots to reflect so clearly on the nature of humanity. A trick adeptly mastered in Star Trek The Next Generation's character "Data". Using a non-human... non-LIVING no less!... character to point out both the depth and the shallowness of humans. This gives Asimov much more freedom because the reader can't dismiss the perspective of the robot (culture, background, circumstance, parenting, etc.) Anyway, nobody did it better than Asimov and this trilogy is well written (if a bit of a light summer read) and worthwhile. While not juvenile fiction, like a lot of earlier SF, this is a great way for a young reader to explore an interest in science and speculation.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2496579813118407269" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

